    "contenu": "The document describes the process of making koji, a fermentation starter crucial in Japanese cuisine. Here’s a structured breakdown of the content:\n\n### Introduction:\n- **Subject Highlighted**: Making koji\n- **Starter Importance**: Starting koji spontaneously using corn husks is mentioned, though using a starter culture is recommended to ensure the presence of the right mold aroma.\n\n### Starter Source:\n- **Provider**: GEM Cultures\n- **Variety**: Offers several koji starters depending on the substrate and the end products.\n- **Personal Preference**: Author prefers barley koji, used in miso, amazaké, and pickles.\n\n### Process Description:\n1. **Preparation Stages**:\n   - **Soak**: Soak the pearled barley overnight.\n   - **Steam**: Steam until cooked, which takes about two hours. Utilize Chinese bamboo steamers lined with a cotton cloth.\n   - **Cool**: Allow the cooked barley to reach body temperature.\n   - **Inoculate**: Inoculate the barley with a starter culture.\n   - **Incubation Temperature**: Maintain at 80-95°F (27-35°C).\n\n2. **Incubation**:\n   - **Duration**: 36 to 48 hours.\n   - **Setup**: Use a lined baking pan or similar vessel covered with an unscented cotton sheet for the barley to sit on during incubation.\n\n3. **Mixing**:\n   - **Stirring**: Stir the inoculated mixture thoroughly before and presumably during the incubation.\n\nThe text also highlights the importance of not being overwhelmed by the choice of different starters, suggesting starting with one and experimenting as you gain experience."
