    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_57",
    "contenu": "The document provides an in-depth look at the process and various aspects related to the production and history of different types of ice cream under the broader topic \"Unfermented Dairy Products\". Below is the structured content of the provided text:\n\n### Unfermented Dairy Products\n\n#### Various Types and Methods of Ice Cream Production:\n\n1. **Soft-serve Ice Cream**:\n   - Comprises additives including corn syrup, powdered milk, and vegetable gums.\n   - Known for being dispensed at a high temperature (20-22°F or -6°C) which contributes to its softness.\n\n2. **Kulfi (Indian Ice Cream)**:\n   - Made without stirring, using milk boiled down to reduce volume and enhance concentration, which brings thick texture and inherent flavors like butterscotch.\n\n3. **Premium-Quality Ice Creams**:\n   - Typically contains more cream and egg yolks compared to less expensive types.\n   - Higher fat content and less air, ensuring a richer texture.\n\n#### Basic Ingredients and Preparation of Ice Cream:\n\n- **Ingredients**: Fresh cream, milk, table sugar, and optionally egg yolks for richness and texture.\n- **Preparation Steps**:\n  1. **Mixing**: Combine ingredients.\n  2. **Pasteurization**: Heat treatment to dissolve and hydrate ingredients.\n  3. **Cooling**: Cools the mix to enhance texture by minimizing ice crystal size.\n\n#### Special Techniques and Innovations in Ice Cream Making:\n\n1. **Freezing Methods**:\n   - Commercial methods often use rapid cooling technologies to freeze the mix instantly.\n\n2. **Historic Technique - Flying Fortress**:\n   - As reported on March 13, 1943, by the New York Times, American air crews made ice cream using the rear gunner's compartment in Flying Fortresses during World War II.\n\n3. **Modern Technique – Using Liquid Nitrogen**:\n   - Popular in chemistry and culinary applications for instant freezing, creating smooth ice cream by instantly chilling the mix at -320°F (-196°C).\n\nThe segment demonstrates the evolution and creativity in ice cream production, advising on both traditional and modern techniques for achieving the desired texture and flavor in ice cream."
