    "source": "and_polenta_to_a_the",
    "contenu": "### Basic Polenta Recipe\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- 4 cups cold water\n- 2 teaspoons salt\n- 1 cup medium- or coarse-grind cornmeal (not instant)\n- 4 tablespoons (½ stick) unsalted butter\n- 3 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese\n\n**Instructions:**\n1. **Traditional Cooking Method:**\n   - Bring salted water to a boil and gradually add cornmeal, stirring constantly to prevent lumps.\n   - Reduce heat to low and simmer slowly, stirring every 5 minutes until the polenta is cooked, which takes about 25 to 45 minutes.\n   - Once foolproof, use a large saucepan and mix cold water, salt, and cornmeal.\n   - Bring to a gradual boil over medium heat, whisking occasionally. Then reduce the heat to low and simmer, stirring with a wooden spoon until creamy and smooth (about 30 minutes).\n   - Stir in butter and Parmesan until melted. Serve warm.\n\n2. **For Softer Polenta:**\n   - Keep the polenta soft by adding hot water in increments as needed.\n\n3. **For Firmer Polenta:**\n   - Pour the soft polenta onto an oiled, rimmed baking sheet.\n   - Refrigerate until set, at least 2 hours or up to 2 days.\n   - Cut into strips and bake, fry, or grill as desired.\n\n4. **Alternative Oven-Cooked Method:**\n   - As per instructions on the package of Golden Pheasant Polenta: Mix cornmeal, water, salt, and melted butter.\n   - Pour into a well-buttered deep baking dish.\n   - Bake in a preheated 350-degree oven for 45 minutes.\n   - Stir, add salt to taste if necessary, and bake for an additional 10 minutes or until fully cooked. \n\nThis structured representation includes the measured ingredients and a detailed, step-by-step procedure divided into methods for achieving different polenta textures and an alternative oven-cooked method."
  },
