    "source": "the-wine-bible-karen-macneil.pdf_page_1069",
    "contenu": "The document discusses the vineyards of Germany with specific focus on vineyard organization and regions. Here is the structured content extracted from the document:\n\n---\n\n**Image Caption:**\nThe steep-terraced vineyards of Herzöglichler Weinberg in Saale-Unstrut in far northern Germany. Vineyards here are often interspersed among stunning medieval castles.\n\n---\n\n**Text Content:**\n\n1. **Overview of German Vineyards:**\n   - Germany's wine production is a small portion of the world's total, with more than twenty thousand grape growers. Despite this, the best estates in Germany are often small but produce a myriad of wines due to the variety of vineyard sites, grape varieties, ripeness levels, and sweetness levels.\n\n2. **Vineyard Location and Naming:**\n   - Vineyards are primarily located in small villages on the edges of the vineyards. The naming convention for German wines typically includes the winery, town, and specific vineyard. Historically, wine purchasing decisions were influenced first by the vineyard's reputation, then the winery, and then by the brand or producer's name.\n\n3. **Historical Context and Legal Changes:**\n   - Before 1971, there were more than thirty thousand individual vineyard names used by wine drinkers. These were consolidated to about 2,600 vineyards after sweeping wine laws were enacted in 1971.\n\n4. **Regional Division:**\n   - Germany is divided into thirteen wine regions. Notably, regions such as Saale Unstrut and Sachsen were added after the reunification of Germany in 1989.\n   - Key regions include Mosel, Rheingau, and Pfalz.\n\n5. **Further Organizational Structure:**\n   - The wine regions are divided into thirty-nine districts called _bereiche_, which in turn contain 167 collections of vineyards known as _grosslage_. Each _grosslage_ consists of several individual vineyard sites called _einzellage_.\n\n6. **Current Status:**\n   - As of 2013, the existing structure includes various levels of vineyard collections and sites, reflecting the detailed and structured approach to wine categorization in Germany.\n\n---\n\nThis document provides a detailed account of the intricate classification and nomenclature of German wine regions and vineyards, reflecting the uniqueness and tradition of German wine production."
