    "source": "inconnu_1161",
    "contenu": "### A SURVEY OF COMMON HERBS\n\n#### Coriander\n- **Name & Origin:** Coriander, also known as cilantro, is native to the Middle East, Southeast Asia, and later spread to China, India, and Latin America.\n- **Description:** The seeds have been found in Bronze Age sites and was known since the time of King Tut. It has rounded, notched, tender leaves that are popular worldwide.\n- **Usage:** Known for replacing cilantro in Spanish speaking regions of America, the herb itself has a distinctive flavor, described occasionally as “soapy.” The fatty aldehyde, decenal, in its aroma provides a distinct citrus note.\n\n#### Fennel\n- **Name & Origin:** A native of the Mediterranean and southwest Asia, resembling dill with feather-like leaves.\n- **Species:** Known scientifically as _Foeniculum vulgare_, three different subspecies exist: _piperitum_ (wild), _vulgare_ (sweet), and _azoricum_ (Florence fennel).\n- **Description and Usage:** Utilized for its anise-like flavor and sharpness in meat and fish dishes. The cultivated variant is known for being sugars sweeter than table sugar, and its bulbs or Florence fennel are used as aromatic vegetables due to their rich phenolic content.\n\n#### Dill\n- **Name & Origin:** Known as _Anethum graveolens_, it is native to southwest Asia and India.\n- **Description:** Features tough, feather-like leaves and was known since ancient Egypt. It has gained popularity in Europe aligning with the local caraway.\n- **Usage:** Employed majorly for its blend of distinctive caraway-like aroma.\n\n#### Lovage\n- **Name & Origin:** Lovage, _Levisticum officinale_, is a herb originating from western Asia.\n- **Description:** Known for its large size and aromatic properties.\n\n#### Sidebar: Carrot Family Anatomy\n- **General Info:** Herbs in the carrot family feature defensive oil glands within their leaves which are ideal for storing and channeling essential oils."
