    "source": "The_Art_of_Fermentation.pdf_page_302",
    "contenu": "The document provides instructions for preparing kvass (a fermented beverage), divided into several steps as outlined below:\n\n1. **Preparation of Bread:**\n   - Use stale bread, preferably past its \"best by\" date.\n   - Chop the bread into large chunks and dry them in a warm oven for about 15 minutes.\n   - Boil water sufficient to cover the bread chunks.\n\n2. **Pre-Fermentation:**\n   - Start with the bread in an open ceramic crock or a large cooking pot.\n   - Add dry herbs like mint.\n   - Pour boiled water over the bread and herbs until all are covered.\n   - Ensure the bread is submerged by placing a plate on top to weigh it down.\n   - Cover the container with a cloth to keep out flies and allow it to sit overnight.\n\n3. **Straining Process:**\n   - In the morning, strain the liquid from the bread solids.\n   - Use a colander lined with a few layers of cheesecloth to collect and squeeze the liquid from the soggy bread.\n   - Knead and press the cheesecloth to extract as much liquid as possible.\n   - Continue until all liquid is strained from the bread.\n\n4. **Fermentation:**\n   - Measure the strained liquid and transfer it to a fermentation jar or crock.\n   - For each gallon or 4 liters of liquid, add a pinch of salt, about ½ cup/125 ml of honey or sugar, the juice of one lemon, and ½ cup/125 ml of sourdough starter, water kefir, or yeast.\n   - Stir thoroughly and cover with a cloth.\n   - Let the mixture ferment for a day or two, stirring occasionally.\n\n5. **Bottling:**\n   - Once the kvass is fermenting vigorously and bubbling, prepare it for bottling.\n   - Ensure bottles are cleaned and review earlier notes on pressure which might build up in the containers during fermentation.\n\nThe final note indicates safety measures regarding bottle fermentation, emphasizing the monitoring of pressure within bottles to prevent accidents."
