    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_620",
    "contenu": "The document provides detailed information about the properties and behavior of gelatin in various culinary applications, particularly in sauces and jellies. Here is a structured summary of its content:\n\n### **Properties of Gelatin**\n- Gelatin molecules bond to form double and triple helixes, which give rigidity to the network of gelatin molecules, turning a liquid into a solid.\n- Stable at 1% concentration but becomes fragile; commercial gelatin desserts typically contain about 3% gelatin or more to ensure firmness.\n\n### **Characteristics of Jellies**\n- When optimal, jellies are translucent and glistening and enhance foods embedded within them.\n- Best gelatin junction temperature is right around body temperature, allowing jellies to melt effortlessly from solid in the mouth to a fluid.\n- Gelatin has a unique quality among thickeners as it can transition smoothly in the mouth without any residual thickness.\n\n### **Gelatin Quality and Concentration**\n- The texture and strength of a jelly are highly dependent on the concentration and quality of the gelatin used.\n- Even manufactured gelatin generally retains only 60–70% of full-length gelatin molecules, the remainder consists of smaller pieces which are less efficient as thickeners.\n\n### **Assessing Gel Strength**\n- To test gel strength, one can cool a spoonful of the gelatin mixture in ice water to see if it sets.\n- Adjustments can be made to increase firmness by concentrating the gelatin or adding pure gelatin for enhancement.\n\n### **Additional Ingredients**\n- Other ingredients mixed into the gel can adjust the overall consistency and strength of the gelatin.\n\n### **Visual Explanation**\n- Illustrated diagrams showing how gelatin molecules interact:\n  - **Hot solution**: Water and protein molecules are in constant, forceful movement.\n  - **Cooling**: Proteins begin forming regions of collagen-like helical associations which trap the liquid within, forming a solid meshwork gel.\n\nThis structured content encapsulates the informational essence conveyed in the document, focusing on the scientific and practical aspects of using gelatin in culinary applications."
