    "source": "inconnu_3246",
    "contenu": "The document appears to be an excerpt from a study or guide about Beaujolais wine, specifically discussing different aspects of Beaujolais Villages and Cru, as well as notable production areas for structured wines within this region.\n\n### Beaujolais Villages and the Beaujolais Crus\n\n- **Location**: The vineyards for Beaujolais Crus are located to the north and west of the region, with 39 villages having the right to call their wine \"Beaujolais Villages.\" These vineyards are planted on rolling hills where granite soils are predominant.\n- **Village Labels**: Individual village names rarely appear on wine labels.\n- **Appellation Rights**: Ten villages have entitlements for their own appellation.\n- **Blending**: Wines typically labelled as Beaujolais Villages are usually made from blends of wines from different villages.\n- **Notable Crus**: There are ten Beaujolais crus, with four having the greatest prominence.\n\n### Production Techniques and Notable Producing Areas\n\n- **Key Producing Areas**: \n  - **Brouilly**\n  - **Morgon**\n  - **Fleurie**\n  - **Moulin-à-Vent** \n  - **Moulin-à-Vent and Morgon** often produce the most structured wines due to the high level of fruit concentration and tannins.\n  \n- **Aging and Production Styles**: \n  - Brouilly and Fleurie generally produce lighter, more perfumed styles. \n  - Techniques include a range from crushed-fruit fermentation to oak ageing (in large vats or casks).\n  - The wines might display nuanced aromas or flavors from new oak.\n\n- **Special Techniques for Enhanced Aromas**:\n  - Other producers opt for semi-carbonic maceration or use a small proportion of whole bunches to enhance brighter fruit aromas in the wine.\n\nThis snapshot focuses on explaining how geographical and technical aspects in Beaujolais contribute to different styles and qualities of wine, highlighting specific practices that affect the outcome of wine production in this famous French wine region."
  },
