    "source": "dokumen.pub_perfect-pairings-a-master-sommeliers-practical-advice-for-partnering-wine-with-food-9780520931664.pdf_page_119",
    "contenu": "The document provides information on the flavors of Gewürztraminer wine and its pairing with food. Here's the structured content outlined in the document:\n\n### Flavors\n- **Fruit:** Apple, pear, peach, apricot, tangerine, lychee, orange or orange zest, passion fruit, pineapple, golden raisin, mango\n- **Floral:** Honeysuckle, tuberose, freesia, gardenia, jasmine, clove, cinnamon, anise, nutmeg, mace\n- **Earth:** Kerosene or fusel oil, smoke, mineral\n- **Wood (if used):** Vanilla, sweet spice\n- **Other:** Pepper, sauerkraut\n\n### Wine and Food Pairing\n\n#### Ingredients and Styles \nGewürztraminer can be a challenging wine to pair with food due to its spiciness and late ripening, which makes it stronger in flavor. It tends not to match well with refreshing or light dishes, but is suitable for strong, spicy foods.\n\n#### Recommended Food Pairing\n- **Classic pairings:** Rich dishes like goose, duck, and turkey.\n  \n- **Special pairings:** \n  - With meats such as pork and veal.\n  - Alsace region dishes like choucroute with pork chops, sausages, potatoes, and sauerkraut.\n  - Seafood options including crab, many sweet shellfish, prawns.\n  - Tarts like egg-based tarts.\n  \n#### Cooking Styles\nGewürztraminer is said to complement:\n- Roasts with bold elements such as curry and ginger.\n  \n#### Special Note\n- Off-dry versions of Gewürztraminer should be paired in the fashion similar to off-dry Rieslings, favoring sweet dessert applications."
  },
