    "source": "docslide-fr-le-repertoire-des-saveurspdf-copie.pdf_page_215",
    "contenu": "The provided image is a document in French, discussing various flavor profiles and combinations involving fruits such as pineapple (ananas), pomelo, apple (pomme), and other ingredients. It provides sensory descriptions and culinary uses for these combinations. Here's a structured summary of the content:\n\n---\n\n### Ananas & Pomélo\n- Flavor combination of pineapple and pomelo.\n- Evokes a sense of tropical relaxation, making one feel as if resting in a hammock or even recalling the Apollo 11 lunar mission.\n- Enhances the sensation of bitterness in certain dishes like salads, while not adversely affecting the perception of other flavors.\n\n### Ananas & Pomme\n- Pineapple and apple combination derives from the Tupi-Guarani word \"naná naná,\" meaning \"perfume of perfumes\".\n- Detectable notes of fresh apple, deep pineapple flavors such as 'reinette allignton' and 'claygate permain' apples are mentioned.\n\n### Ananas & Porc\n- Focuses on a combination popular in Mexico, suggesting enjoying spiced pork (like tacos al pastor) with pineapple.\n- The blend of pork and the enzyme bromelain from pineapple helps tenderize the meat and imparts a caramelized crust.\n\n### Ananas & Raisin (See Raisin & Ananas)\n- Suggests further reading or exploration under a section titled \"Raisin & Ananas\".\n\n### Ananas & Sauge\n- Pineapple paired with sage (Salvia elegans), known for its long flowering time and bright red hue.\n- Commonly used to aromatize drinks or salads.\n- Mentioned by Dolf De Rovira Senior as having a pineapple flavor that enhances piña colada.\n\n### Ananas & Vanille\n- Discusses a pineapple and vanilla pairing, popularized by Dole through a recipe for an upside-down pineapple cake from the 1920s.\n- Provides a sensory experience of caramelized, creamy, and rich vanilla which complements various upside-down cakes.\n\n### Pomme (Apple)\n- Describes the refreshing and fruity flavor of apples, ranging from sweet to tart.\n- Mentions various apple types from 'fuji' to 'bramley,' highlighting the floral to extremely acidic profiles.\n- Apples carry additional notes like musky, floral, and fruity tones such as quetsche, pear, pineapple, and others.\n\nEach section elaborates on how these flavors and combinations influence culinary practices and the sensory experiences they evoke, highlighting specific attributes and potential uses in cooking and preparation."
